'''Henry Twist''' (January 30, 1870 - May 16, 1934) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[coal mining|miner's]] agent and [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] politician.

Twist was born at [[Platt Bridge]], near [[Wigan]], [[Lancashire]], and after [[primary education]] at the local [[Wesleyan]] School, began employment at Bamfurlong coal mine at the age of eleven.<ref name=obit>''Obituary: Mr Henry Twist'', The Times, May 18, 1934, p.16</ref> At the age of thirty he became a checkweighman at the mine, having also been elected to the [[Wigan Rural District|Wigan Rural District Council]]. In 1906 he succeeded [[Sam Woods]] as the area's agent for the Lancashire and Cheshire Miner's Federation, and was the organisation's vice-president in 1929. He subsequently served on the executive of the [[Miners' Federation of Great Britain]].<ref name=obit/>

Twist was twice elected to the [[United Kingdom House of Commons|House of Commons]] as a Labour [[member of parliament]]. At the [[United Kingdom general election, 1910 (January)|January 1910 general election]] he became [[Wigan (UK Parliament constituency)|Wigan's]] first Labour MP. However he was defeated at the subsequent [[United Kingdom general election, 1910 (December)|contest in December of the same year]]. At the [[United Kingdom general election, 1922|1922 general election]] he was returned as member for [[Leigh (UK Parliament constituency)|Leigh]], another Lancashire coal-mining constituency. However he was forced to retire due to ill health and did not stand at [[United Kingdom general election, 1923|subsequent election in 1923]].

Henry Twist died in [[Blackpool]] in May 1934, aged 64.<ref name=obit/>

